  "prompt": "Which problems should I attempt first on TopCoder?",
  "response": "When getting started on TopCoder, it's important to approach problems methodically to build your skills and confidence. Here are some tips on how to choose which problems to attempt first:\n\n1. **Start with Easy Problems**: Look for problems labeled as \"easy\" or \"1-point\" problems. These are designed to help newcomers understand the platform and basic problem-solving techniques.\n\n2. **Practice Archive**: TopCoder has a practice archive where you can filter problems by difficulty. Start with the easiest problems and gradually work your way up to moderate ones as you gain confidence.\n\n3. **Settle on a Track**: Depending on your interests, you might want to focus on different areas such as algorithms, data structures, or specific domains (e.g., dynamic programming, graphs). Select problems that align with these areas.\n\n4. **Use Tutorials**: Many problems have associated tutorials or editorials. After attempting a problem (even if you don't solve it), read the editorial to understand the solution and learn new techniques.\n\n5. **Analyze Past Competitions**: Review problems from recent contests and filter by difficulty. Often, problems in earlier rounds are more accessible for beginners.\n\n6. **Compete Frequently**: Participate in regular contests to get accustomed to the competitive environment. Pay attention to the problems that seem difficult to you and revisit them at a later date.\n\n7. **Join the Community**: Engaging with other TopCoder users can provide insights into which problems to focus on and recommendations for practice.\n\n8. **Keep a Challenge Journal**: Document which problems you tried and what strategies worked or didn't. This will help track your progress and identify areas needing improvement.\n\nIn summary, start with easier problems, engage with the community, and gradually challenge yourself with more difficult problems as your skills improve. Consistent practice and learning from mistakes will help you grow as a competitive programmer.",
